Overview

This notebook extends the modeling done in 2013 to include data through much of 2018.

Load Data

Loading cleaned and transformed giving data:

df <- readRDS("../data/Cleaned and Transformed Giving Data.rds")
head(df)

Columns to Accomodate Analysis

I’ll add a few columns to enable asking analysis “what if’s” and adjust for anomolies:

library("dplyr", quietly=TRUE, warn.conflicts = FALSE)
df <- mutate(df, 
             excluded = FALSE, 
             removed.amount = 0, 
             original.total = total)

Accommodating Unusual Gift

12/26/2016 had an unusual single gift skewing analyses. Other large gifts have been recieved over this period but this gift was at least twice all others. I’m removing the amount of the unusual gift from the month’s total. Previously I excluded that month all-together, but I’ve commented that line out so no values are excluded.

df$removed.amount[as.Date(df$week.ending) == "2016-12-25"] <- 20000
df$total <- df$original.total - df$removed.amount
#df$excluded[as.Date(df$week.ending) == "2016-12-25"] <- TRUE

Note: we’re not excluding the 3 months consider “outliers” in the 2013 analysis. Now with 9 years of history, those months don’t appear as much to be outliers.

Modeling

Regressing the R version of the 2013 model: \[\textit{Monthly Giving} = a+b_{year}+c_{month}\]

mod <- lm(
  formula = total ~
    year + month,
  data = df[df$excluded!=TRUE,]
)

Model Generalization

Due to R’s conventions, the model coefficients, as regressed by R: \[\textit{Monthly Giving} = a+b_{year}+c_{month}\] are regressed relative to \(month_1\)=January (\(c_{January}=0\)) and \(year_1\)=2010 (\(b_{2010}=0\)). This is why there is no year2010 nor monthJanuary coeffiencients. A more useful set of references for forecasting would be “an average month” and “an average year”. Thus we can modify the model as such: \[ \begin{aligned} \begin{split} \textit{Monthly Giving} &= a+(\overline{b_{year}}+b_{year}-\overline{b_{year}})+ (\overline{c_{month}}+c_{month}-\overline{c_{month}}) \\ &= \big[a+\overline{b_{year}}+\overline{c_{month}}\big]+ \big(b_{year}-\overline{b_{year}}\big)+ \big(c_{month}-\overline{c_{month}}\big) \end{split} \end{aligned} \] where \(\overline{b_{year}}\) is the mean of \(b_{year}\) coefficients, including \(b_{2010}=0\), and \(\overline{c_{month}}\) is the mean of the \(c_{year}\) coefficients, including \(c_{January}=0\). The term \(\big[a+\overline{b_{year}}+\overline{c_{month}}\big]\) is then the regressed \(\textit{Monthly Giving}\) for an average month in an average year over the period covered by the data. Of course no actual month or year is the average, and to reproduce a given month and year prediction the shifted coefficients \((b_{year}-\overline{b_{year}}) \text{ and } (c_{month}-\overline{c_{month}})\) must be employed. However, this facilitates using the model for monthly variance predictions in the upcoming year since: \[ \begin{aligned} \begin{split} \textit{Average Monthly Giving}_\textit{next year} &=\big[a+\overline{b_{year}}+\overline{c_{month}}\big]+\big(b_\textit{next year}-\overline{b_{year}}\big) \\ &=\frac{\textit{Projected Income}_\textit{next year}}{12} \end{split} \end{aligned} \] So even though we don’t know \(b_\textit{next year}\) we can make an estimation for next year’s total \(\textit{Projected Income}\) and get monthly estimates based on the annual estimate:

\[ \textit{Monthly Giving}_\textit{next year} =\frac{\textit{Projected Income}_\textit{next year}}{12} + \big(c_{month}-\overline{c_{month}}\big) \]

Monthly Variation

This plot shows the resulting \(month\) regression coeffiecients shifted by \(\overline{c_{month}}\) capturing month-to-month variation. (\((c_{month}-\overline{c_{month}})\)) The shape of the yearly repeated pattern in the prediction are the result of these terms.

This plot is generally similar to Figure 13 in the 2013 Analysis with the exception of November. Since it is based on 9 years of Seed history, I’ll judge that it is more representative of an average year.
